tags.description:
An Asset Definition represents a composable type definition for inventory assets in Cumulocity.  
It describes the structure, composition, and allowed relationships of assets.

While Property Definitions describe individual data structures, an Asset Definition combines multiple Property Definitions into a higher-level composite model — forming the blueprint for complex digital twins such as machines, vehicles, or buildings.

An Asset Definition is both:

- Composable — it aggregates multiple Property Definitions and their schemas into a single JSON object schema, and
- Hierarchical — it can define parent-child relationships between assets.

Each Asset Definition acts as a meta-model describing:

- Which properties an asset may have,
- Which sub-assets (children) it may contain, and
- Whether additional (unlisted) properties or sub-assets are allowed.

### Structure of an Asset Definition

An Asset Definition typically contains:

- A unique identifier (`identifier`)
- A composition object specifying allowed properties and sub-assets
- Optional metadata

```JSON
{
  "identifier": "c8y_Windfarm",
  "composition": {
    "allowedProperties": [],
    "allowedSubAssets": [],
    "additionalProperties": false,
    "additionalSubAssets": false
  }
}
```

The composition defines how an asset is built from Property Definitions and sub-assets:

- `allowedProperties` — a set of entries referencing the identifiers of Property Definitions that compose this asset.
- `allowedSubAssets` — a set of entries referencing other Asset Definitions that can appear as children.
- `additionalProperties` — a boolean flag allowing additional (unspecified) properties to be added dynamically.
- `additionalSubAssets` — a boolean flag allowing additional sub-assets beyond those explicitly defined.

Below is an example of an Asset Definition for a Windfarm that consists of multiple properties and sub-assets:

```JSON
{
  "identifier": "c8y_Windfarm",
  "composition": {
    "allowedProperties": [
      {
        "identifier": "c8y_Position",
        "minOccurs": "1"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "c8y_Status",
        "minOccurs": "0"
      }
    ],
    "allowedSubAssets": [
      {
        "identifier": "c8y_Windturbine",
        "minOccurs": "1",
        "maxOccurs": "10"
      }
    ],
    "additionalProperties": false,
    "additionalSubAssets": false
  }
}
```

Explanation of the example:

- The Asset Definition `c8y_Windfarm` composes several Property Definitions (`c8y_Position`, `c8y_Status`).
- It allows up to 10 sub-assets of type `c8y_Windturbine`.
- Additional properties and sub-assets are not allowed to enforce a fixed structure.
- You can control whether a property or sub-asset is required by setting `minOccurs: 1` (required) or `minOccurs: 0` (optional).

### JSON Schema Composition in Asset Definitions

When an Asset Definition is created (or updated), its JSON Schema is automatically generated.
The JSON Schema is generated by composing the schemas of all allowed Property Definitions specified in the Asset Definition.
Each allowed Property Definition contributes its individual schema, which is composed into a single, higher-level JSON object schema representing the complete asset.

Consider an Asset Definition for a Windfarm that includes `c8y_Position` as an allowed Property Definition. The final, composed JSON Schema is:

```JSON
{
  "jsonSchema": {
    "additionalProperties": false,
    "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
    "type": "object",
    "definitions": {
      "c8y_Position": {
        "title": "Location",
        "type": "object",
        "additionalProperties": false,
        "properties": {
          "lng": {
            "type": "number"
          },
          "lat": {
            "type": "number"
          },
          "alt": {
            "type": "number"
          }
        },
        "required": [
          "lat",
          "lng"
        ]
      }
    },
    "properties": {
      "c8y_Position": {
        "$ref": "#/definitions/c8y_Position"
      }
    },
    "required": [
      "c8y_Position"
    ]
  }
}
```
